[Comment "short-sweet-the-petroff/course/17076, variation/1613043"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4] This is the Petroff Defence, also 
known as Russian Defence. Black's main idea in this opening is to not cover the 
e5-pawn, but rather play for a counterattack against e4 instead. White attacked 
e5, we simply do the same with the e4-pawn. I need to emphasize that taking the 
pawn on e4 is highly desirable in the open games in general. This is also the 
reason why the Berlin Defence to the Ruy Lopez is such a pain for White - Black 
often gets to take e4! In the Petroff usually both e-pawns are being captured in 
the next moves, leading to a position with an open e-file. This is an important 
observation: you will get a rather open position in the Petroff most of the 
time. There is no 'closed' Petroff or anything of the sort. If you are looking 
for open positions where piece play is important, the Petroff might be the 
opening for you. I mentioned that the e-file is open most of the time. This fact 
is also the reason why the Petroff has the reputation of being a boring opening. 
There have been many games where both players just used the open file for a 
chopping block, trading down to dull boredom. However, this is not happening all 
of the time, of course. There are many fascinating, sharp lines, that are 
extremely tactical and fun to play. As usual, it depends on both player's 
intentions. You can generate a fight from all positions if both sides are up for 
it. The perfect example for this fact is the game between Vladimir Kramnik and 
Fabiano Caruana from the Berlin Candidates 2018, one of the most fascinating and 
also important games of the year so far. There is exactly one scenario where the 
Petroff is the wrong opening, and this is a very rare one. This scenario would 
be Black being in a total must-win-situation against a very strong opponent who 
just needs a draw to achieve a desired result and does not need to play for a 
win at all. This is a rare occasion and one that requires extreme measures - not 
a case for the Petroff, but for a risky (and less sound!) opening. As mentioned, 
the Petroff is not very popular, in particular at the amateur/club level. This 
fact is actually a huge incentive to include it into your repertoire. White 
players simply don't face this opening frequently and therefore have no or 
little preparation against it. Statistically, only about 10% of the games after 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 feature the Petroff (depending on the used database of course, 
but the ballpark figure is correct). White players don't study the Petroff, 
because they don't see the need as it happens so rarely - a reasonable approach 
if you follow the 80/20 rule. However, it is an approach at we may use in our 
favour, of course. If you know the Petroff well, you will be an uncomfortable 
opponent! Ask some White 1. e4 players what they think of facing the Petroff and 
you'll see what I am talking about.} 3. d4 ({White's main move against the 
Petroff always has been and still is} 3. Nxe5 {. However, going 3. d4 is 
perfectly logical as well and White's most important alternative to 3. Nxe5.}) 
Nxe4 {Take e4 whenever possible!} 4. dxe5 {This move has gained some ground in 
recent years, mostly due to the fact that White is getting nowhere in the 
traditional lines. Black has a fine position though, with natural moves to 
play.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4][%csl Re4]} Nxd2 6. Bxd2 Be7 7. 
Bd3 c5 {[%cal Bb8c6][%csl Gc6]} 8. c3 Nc6 {[%cal Be8g8,Bc8g4,Bd8d7] This 
position was reached in a crucial game at the Berlin Candidates between 
Alexander Grischuk and Fabiano Caruana. Caruana went on to win this game and 
qualified for the World Championship Match. Black develops easily and enjoys a 
good central control. We will castle kingside and develop with ...Bg4 and ... 
Qd7, connecting rooks.} *

