1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {This is the Petroff Defence, also known as Russian Defence. 
Black's main idea in this opening is to not cover the e5-pawn, but rather play 
for a counterattack against e4 instead. White attacked e5, we simply do the same 
with the e4-pawn. I need to emphasize that taking the pawn on e4 is highly 
desirable in the open games in general. This is also the reason why the Berlin 
Defence to the Ruy Lopez is such a pain for White - Black often gets to take e4! 
In the Petroff usually both e-pawns are being captured in the next moves, 
leading to a position with an open e-file. This is an important observation: you 
will get a rather open position in the Petroff most of the time. There is no 
'closed' Petroff or anything of the sort. If you are looking for open positions 
where piece play is important, the Petroff might be the opening for you. I 
mentioned that the e-file is open most of the time. This fact is also the reason 
why the Petroff has the reputation of being a boring opening. There have been 
many games where both players just used the open file for a chopping block, 
trading down to dull boredom. However, this is not happening all of the time, of 
course. There are many fascinating, sharp lines, that are extremely tactical and 
fun to play. As usual, it depends on both player's intentions. You can generate 
a fight from all positions if both sides are up for it. The perfect example for 
this fact is the game between Vladimir Kramnik and Fabiano Caruana from the 
Berlin Candidates 2018, one of the most fascinating and also important games of 
the year so far. There is exactly one scenario where the Petroff is the wrong 
opening, and this is a very rare one. This scenario would be Black being in a 
total must-win-situation against a very strong opponent who just needs a draw to 
achieve a desired result and does not need to play for a win at all. This is a 
rare occasion and one that requires extreme measures - not a case for the 
Petroff, but for a risky (and less sound!) opening. As mentioned, the Petroff is 
not very popular, in particular at the amateur/club level. This fact is actually 
a huge incentive to include it into your repertoire. White players simply don't 
face this opening frequently and therefore have no or little preparation against 
it. Statistically, only about 10% of the games after 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 feature the 
Petroff (depending on the used database of course, but the ballpark figure is 
correct). White players don't study the Petroff, because they don't see the need 
as it happens so rarely - a reasonable approach if you follow the 80/20 rule. 
However, it is an approach at we may use in our favour, of course. If you know 
the Petroff well, you will be an uncomfortable opponent! Ask some White 1. e4 
players what they think of facing the Petroff and you'll see what I am talking 
about.} 3. Nc3 ({White basically 'declines' the Petroff with this solid move. 
Now Black has mostly two options. There is} 3. Nc3 3... Bb4 {, but this does not 
equalize after} 4. Nxe5 {.}) ({The best move and usual choice of Petroff experts 
is to go} 3. Nc3 3... Nc6 {, transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) Nc6 4. d4 
{White chooses the Scotch Four Knights. It is a very sound opening, focused on 
rapid development and a sound pawn structure. I recommend to play the main line 
and use a new idea on move 9 to set White some problems. Move 9 sounds like a 
late spot for a new idea, but White's earlier deviations are clearly less 
testing for Black and rather often even give Black an advantage.} exd4 5. Nxd4 
Bb4 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb4e1][%csl Re4]} 6. Nxc6 {[%cal Bf1d3] The e4-pawn was 
attacked and White would like to play Bd3 to cover it. Taking on c6 first is the 
only way to do that.} bxc6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O d5 {Black has managed to play 
...d5, one of the main goals in the open games. If we are able to get this move 
in we are usually fine - this is no exception.} 9. exd5 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1][%csl 
Rd1] This is the innovation I was talking about. Black plays this intermediate 
move, attacking the queen. Now the game gets very tactical.} 10. f3 {This move 
is the only attempt to refute Black's idea. It does not achieve its intended 
goal, but needs to be examined carefully by Black players as it is probably the 
main choice of players who are surprised by 9... Bg4.} Bh5 11. dxc6 {White grabs 
the second pawn, the most principled decision. It is not scary at all for Black, 
though.} Qd4+ {[%cal Gb4c3][%csl Rg1]} 12. Kh1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qxc3 14. Bf4 Qxc6 
{[%cal Bh5g6,Gg6d3] And Black has regained both pawns and is fine. A future 
...Bg6 will get rid of the pair of bishops.} *

