as it happens so rarely - a reasonable approach if you follow the 80/20 rule. 
However, it is an approach at we may use in our favour, of course. If you know 
the Petroff well, you will be an uncomfortable opponent! Ask some White 1. e4 
players what they think of facing the Petroff and you'll see what I am talking 
about.} 3. Nc3 ({White basically 'declines' the Petroff with this solid move. 
Now Black has mostly two options. There is} 3. Nc3 3... Bb4 {, but this does not 
equalize after} 4. Nxe5 {.}) ({The best move and usual choice of Petroff experts 
is to go} 3. Nc3 3... Nc6 {, transposing to the Four Knights Game.}) Nc6 4. Bc4 
{This is the Italian Four Knights. Black is happy to face it - there is a very 
attractive, forceful reply available.} Nxe4 {[%cal Bd7d5,Gd5c4,Gd5e4] The knight 
temporarily sacrifices itself on e4 and thus eliminates the central pawn. As 
mentioned before: this is desirable in the open games in general.} 5. Nxe4 d5 
{[%csl Rc4,Re4]} 6. Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 {[%cal Be8g8,Bf7f5] Black has regained 
the piece and a comfortable game. All pieces can be developed to active 
positions and the pawn structure in perfectly sound.} *

