1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {This is the Petroff Defence, also known as Russian Defence. 
Black's main idea in this opening is to not cover the e5-pawn, but rather play 
for a counterattack against e4 instead. White attacked e5, we simply do the same 
with the e4-pawn. I need to emphasize that taking the pawn on e4 is highly 
desirable in the open games in general. This is also the reason why the Berlin 
Defence to the Ruy Lopez is such a pain for White - Black often gets to take e4! 
In the Petroff usually both e-pawns are being captured in the next moves, 
leading to a position with an open e-file. This is an important observation: you 
will get a rather open position in the Petroff most of the time. There is no 
'closed' Petroff or anything of the sort. If you are looking for open positions 
where piece play is important, the Petroff might be the opening for you. I 
mentioned that the e-file is open most of the time. This fact is also the reason 
why the Petroff has the reputation of being a boring opening. There have been 
many games where both players just used the open file for a chopping block, 
trading down to dull boredom. However, this is not happening all of the time, of 
course. There are many fascinating, sharp lines, that are extremely tactical and 
fun to play. As usual, it depends on both player's intentions. You can generate 
a fight from all positions if both sides are up for it. The perfect example for 
this fact is the game between Vladimir Kramnik and Fabiano Caruana from the 
Berlin Candidates 2018, one of the most fascinating and also important games of 
the year so far. There is exactly one scenario where the Petroff is the wrong 
opening, and this is a very rare one. This scenario would be Black being in a 
total must-win-situation against a very strong opponent who just needs a draw to 
achieve a desired result and does not need to play for a win at all. This is a 
rare occasion and one that requires extreme measures - not a case for the 
Petroff, but for a risky (and less sound!) opening. As mentioned, the Petroff is 
not very popular, in particular at the amateur/club level. This fact is actually 
a huge incentive to include it into your repertoire. White players simply don't 
face this opening frequently and therefore have no or little preparation against 
it. Statistically, only about 10% of the games after 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 feature the 
Petroff (depending on the used database of course, but the ballpark figure is 
correct). White players don't study the Petroff, because they don't see the need 
as it happens so rarely - a reasonable approach if you follow the 80/20 rule. 
However, it is an approach at we may use in our favour, of course. If you know 
the Petroff well, you will be an uncomfortable opponent! Ask some White 1. e4 
players what they think of facing the Petroff and you'll see what I am talking 
about.} 3. Nxe5 {White's main move by far. It is very natural to take the pawn 
anyway, but the current state of theory also suggests it is the most testing 
move.} d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 {The Modern Main Line of the Petroff. Around the 
year 2000 White got increasingly frustrated with the traditional lines against 
the Petroff. The search for new ideas quickly led to 5. Nc3.} Nxc3 ({I need to 
mention that I have played} 5... Nf6 {here in a classical time control game. 
This move is non-theoretical option that basically admits that White is just a 
little bit better, but it's not much. I went for this line before I had studied 
any Petroff theory - just as a surprise weapon. Now I would go for 5... Nxc3 for 
sure, it is the more logical move.}) 6. dxc3 {This pawn structure is a key 
element of the Modern Main Line. White will castle queenside and his king will 
be very safe behind the shield of four pawns.} Be7 7. Be3 Nc6 ({I suggest to 
place the knight on c6, being flexible about the side to castle. Most of the 
time we will castle queenside, but in some cases kingside castling is fine as 
well. That being said,} 7... O-O {is a viable alternative that leads to very 
sharp play. White will castle to the other side, so both sides may play for an 
attack on the king. My choice is the more conservative one, the one that is 
easier to play.}) 8. Qd2 Be6 {[%cal Bd8d7,Be8c8]} 9. O-O-O Qd7 {[%csl Rg7,Ra7] 
The tabiya of the Modern Main line. Here White has tried a lot of moves and 
plans, often trying to trick Black with slightly different move orders. White 
has two ideas available that need to be mentioned. The first and actually less 
dangerous one is the knight sortie to g5. White takes a look at the e6-bishop 
and intends to take this piece, gaining the bishop pair. Black usually does not 
want to give up the e6-bishop, it is the more active bishop, compared to the one 
on e7. This also explains why many players simply take the knight on g5 with the 
e7-bishop, proceeded by playing ...f6 and queenside castling. This approach is 
perfectly viable, but it is still a small concession to give up the pair of 
bishops. I recommend to avoid this scenario by reacting with ...Bf5, moving the 
bishop away. This is only possible if you are careful with your move orders - 
for example, you need to make sure that f7 is covered when you move the bishop 
away from e6. White's main idea in this line, however, is to play Nd4 at an 
opportune moment. As mentioned, Black usually does not want to give up the 
e6-bishop, so the principled reply to Nd4 is to take the knight. Now, after 
White has recaptured with a piece, there is a potential double attack on g7 and 
a7. Currently a7 is covered, but Black likes to castle queenside - and exactly 
after queenside castling a7 is not protected anymore. Typical ideas for Black 
include moves like ...h6 (addresses Ng5 ideas after queenside castling), ...Rg8 
(covering g7 against attacks after a trading sequence on d4) and ...a6, removing 
the pawn from attacks after a later ...O-O-O being played.} 10. Kb1 {This is the 
most popular move at this point. Moving the king to b1 is an almost universally 
useful choice after queenside castling. There is the saying that 'long castling' 
is called 'long because it actually takes two moves - you play O-O-O and Kb1. 
That being said, White has lots of other moves available that improve the 
position slightly and angle for an improved version of Nd4. Against 10. Kb1 
Black has a more direct option that we will explore in the following line.} Bf6 
{[%cal Gd7f7,Be8c8] This activated the bishop, but it has additional benefits. 
Now f7 is covered by the queen, so a future O-O-O is possible without any fear 
of Ng5. You can simply move ...Bf5 then and send the knight back later.} 11. h4 
{White gains some kingside space, but also introduces the idea to recapture on 
g5 with a pawn in case of a later Ng5 or Bg5. This scenario would be quite awful 
for Black, but we have no problem to avoid it.} O-O-O 12. Nd4 ({Instead} 12. Ng5 
{is no problem, as already discussed. We just move the bishop away with} 12... 
Bf5 {.}) Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Be5 {This is the important point of Black's play. Black 
avoids a doubled pawn on f6 and the a7 pawn is protected by tactical means. 
Black did not experience any problems in the latest game on the highest level 
between Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Fabiano Caruana, played at the Sinquefield 
Cup in 2018.} 14. Bxa7 {This was avoided in the mentioned game, of course. But 
I'd like to demonstrate why this is a poisoned pawn.} Qa4 {[%cal 
Ga4a7,Ga4a2,Ge6a2][%csl Ra2,Ra7] And this double attack wins! The a7-bishop is 
attacked and at the same time Qxa2+ in threatened, mating in two moves! This 
will cost White a piece and the game.} *

